11 "§ 120-4.60. Staff.
12 (a) The Commission shall be administratively housed in the Legislative Services Office
13 of the General Assembly.
14 (b) The Commission may exercise its prescribed powers independently of the General
15 Assembly and the Legislative Services Officer. In order to pay expenses incidental to
16 implementing its purposes, the Commission may enter into contracts, own property, and accept
17 funds, grants, and gifts from academic and nonprofit entities that have never contributed to
18 political parties, persons holding public office, or candidates for public office.
19 (c) The Legislative Services Officer shall provide general administrative support to the
20 Commission, including purchasing, payroll, and similar administrative services.
21 (d) The Commission shall retain independent staff under contract, including an executive
22 secretary and any additional necessary supporting staff. As a whole, the political affiliations of
23 staff members, or lack thereof, shall be divided approximately into thirds among the two political
24 parties with the highest number of affiliates and among persons unaffiliated with a political party.
25 A person is ineligible to serve as a staff member to the Commission if that person would be
26 ineligible to serve as a member of the Commission pursuant to G.S. 120-4.55(b). Staff shall be
27 selected as follows:
28 (1) If there are at least three members appointed to the Commission from each
29 sub-sub-subdivision of G.S. 120-4.55(c)(3)b., staff shall be selected by a vote
30 of at least nine members composed of at least three members appointed to the
31 Commission from each sub-sub-subdivision of G.S. 120-4.55(c)(3)b.
32 (2) If there are not at least three members appointed to the Commission from each
33 sub-sub-subdivision of G.S. 120-4.55(c)(3)b., staff shall be selected by a vote
34 of all of the following:
35 a. At least three members from each sub-sub-subdivision of
36 G.S. 120-4.55(c)(3)b. with more than three members appointed to the
37 Commission.
38 b. A unanimous vote from each sub-sub-subdivision of
39 G.S. 120-4.55(c)(3)b. with three or fewer members appointed to the
40 Commission.
41 "§ 120-4.65. Open meetings and public records.
42 The Commission shall be subject to the Public Records Act, Chapter 132 of the General
43 Statutes, and the Open Meetings Law, Article 33C of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, except
44 to the extent those enactments conflict with the below requirements:
45 (1) Members of the Commission and staff shall not discuss the business of the
46 Commission outside public meetings.
47 (2) If a member of the Commission violates subdivision (1) of this section, he or
48 she shall place in the public records of the Commission (i) any violating
49 written communication and (ii) a written description of any violating oral
50 communication. The written description of an oral communication must
51 include the name of the parties to the communication, the date and
