21 "§ 120-4.80. Public input.
22 (a) Public Hearings. – For each redistricting cycle, the Commission shall engage in a
23 minimum of 25 public hearings. At least one public hearing shall occur in each of the
24 metropolitan and micropolitan statistical areas of the State. Of the total public hearings, at least
25 10 hearings shall occur before a preliminary plan is released to the public, and at least 10 hearings
26 shall occur after a preliminary plan is released to the public but before a proposed or alternative
27 plan is released to the public.
28 (b) Public Input. – To the extent possible, the Commission shall facilitate the ability of
29 members of the public to provide substantive comments on any plan released to the public. To
30 achieve that goal, the Commission shall provide members of the public with all of the following:
31 (1) Sufficient time to review any plan released to the public.
32 (2) The opportunity to communicate comments, questions, and recommendations
33 on any plan released to the public, at a minimum, in person, online, and
34 through the mail. The Commission shall reserve time at the end of every
35 meeting for in-person and virtual public comment.
36 (3) Access to the same demographic data that is used by the Commission in a
37 machine-readable form.
38 (4) Access to mapping software and census data in a minimum of 30 public library
39 facilities in the State within 20 days of receipt of that data from the United
40 States Bureau of the Census.
41 (5) A public, written response to every substantive comment or recommendation
42 regarding a specific component of a plan released to the public. The response
43 shall address the viability of any recommendation and indicate whether it was
44 or will be incorporated in any other plan. A single response may be provided
45 for one or more comments or recommendations on the same topic.
46 (6) At the conclusion of the redistricting process, the Commission shall publish a
47 written evaluation of each final plan, including at least the following
48 information:
49 a. The impact of the plans on the ability of minority groups, including
50 racial minorities, to elect candidates of their choice.
Page 10 DRS45438-MTye-149

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. The degree to which the plans preserve or divide communities of
2 interest.
3 c. The rationale for changes in the plans from the prior districts.
4 d. The impact of the plans on the metropolitan and micropolitan
5 statistical areas of the State.
6 e. A summary of the public input received by the Commission on the
7 plans.
8 f. An explanation of how the plans comply with the redistricting criteria
9 provided in G.S. 120-4.70.
10 (7) A website with all of the following information:
11 a. Background information on the redistricting process available in at
12 least English and Spanish on the purpose of redistricting and its impact
13 on all communities. The Commission shall provide information in
14 other languages if at least 50,000 people petition the Commission to
15 have a particular language included.
16 b. Livestreams and recordings of all public meetings in audio, video, or
17 both formats and minutes from those meetings.
18 c. Meeting announcements.
19 d. A searchable database of feedback, including public comments, and
20 plans discussed by the Commission. This information shall be made
21 available as soon as practicable after it is generated.
22 e. Plans discussed by the Commission and the data used to create those
23 plans.
24 "§ 120-4.85. Local redistricting.
25 The General Assembly may by law assign to the Commission the duty to prepare district
26 plans for any county, city, town, special district, and other governmental subdivision, if the
27 governing board of the unit or a court of appropriate jurisdiction so requests."
28 SECTION 1.(h) Notwithstanding G.S. 120-4.55(e), as enacted by this act, for any
29 redistricting that may occur prior to the return of the 2030 federal census, the term of office for
30 members of the North Carolina Citizens Redistricting Commission shall begin on January 1,
31 2027, and conclude on June 30, 2030.
32
33 PART II. CONFORMING CHANGES
34 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 120-2.3 reads as rewritten:
35 "§ 120-2.3. Contents of judgments invalidating apportionment or redistricting acts.
36 Every order or judgment declaring unconstitutional or otherwise invalid, in whole or in part
37 and for any reason, any act of the General Assembly plan that apportions or redistricts State
38 legislative or congressional districts shall find with specificity all facts supporting that
39 declaration, shall state separately and with specificity the court's conclusions of law on that
40 declaration, and shall, with specific reference to those findings of fact and conclusions of law,
41 identify every defect found by the court, both as to the plan as a whole and as to individual
42 districts."
43 SECTION 2.(b) G.S. 120-2.4 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 120-2.4. Opportunity for General Assembly to remedy defects.
45 (a) If the General Assembly enacts a plan apportioning or redistricting State legislative
46 or congressional districts, districts becomes effective, in no event may a court impose its own
47 substitute plan unless the court first gives the General Assembly North Carolina Citizens
48 Redistricting Commission a period of time to remedy any defects identified by the court in its
49 findings of fact and conclusions of law. That period of time shall not be less than two weeks,
50 provided, however, that if the General Assembly is scheduled to convene legislative session
DRS45438-MTye-149 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 within 45 days of the date of the court order that period of time shall not be less than two weeks
2 from the convening of that legislative session.weeks.
3 (a1) In the event the General Assembly North Carolina Citizens Redistricting Commission
4 does not act to remedy any identified defects to its plan within that period of time, the court may
5 impose an interim districting plan for use in the next general election only, but that interim
6 districting plan may differ from the previous districting plan enacted by the General Assembly
7 only to the extent necessary to remedy any defects identified by the court.
8 (b) Notwithstanding any other provision of law or authority of the State Board of
9 Elections under Chapter 163 of the General Statutes, the State Board of Elections shall have no
10 authority to alter, amend, correct, impose, or substitute any plan apportioning or redistricting
11 State legislative or congressional districts other than a plan imposed by a court under this section
12 or a plan enacted by the General Assembly.adopted by the North Carolina Citizens Redistricting
13 Commission."
14
15 PART III. EFFECTIVE DATE
16 SECTION 3.(a) If the constitutional amendments proposed by subsections (a), (b),
17 (c), and (d) of Section 1 of this act are approved by the qualified voters as provided in subsections
18 (e) and (f) of Section 1 of this act, the following shall become effective January 1, 2027:
19 (1) Subsections (g) and (h) of Section 1 of this act.
20 (2) Part II of this act.
21 SECTION 3.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
22 law.
